    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm looking at my student loan statement and the principal isn't going down as fast as i thought it would. i'm making my full payments every month but it feels like nothing is happening. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated each month and why it feels like the balance barely moves at first?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The principal isn't shrinking as fast as you'd like because, in the early stages of most loans, the interest accrues on the outstanding balance, and a large portion of your fixed monthly payment goes toward covering that interest first. It's like a little, persistent tide of debt that the interest keeps pushing against your principal payment. Think of it like a slow-moving, slightly sticky patch of ground where the first few steps of your payment are just keeping you from sinking further into the mud. As your balance shrinks, the interest charge each month also decreases, allowing more of your payment to finally start attacking the principal.",
      "source": "target",
